 the Union was defeated; and the 1964 presidential campaign, when Barry Goldwater’s challenge to the New Deal order was soundly defeated by Lyndon B. Johnson. In each of these cases, the very mechanisms that caused the initial failures facilitated their eventual success. After the dust of the immediate political defeat settled, these seemingly discredited ideas and programs disrupted political convention by prevailing, often subverting, and occasionally enhancing constitutional fidelity. Tulis and Mellow present a nuanced story of winning and losing and offer a new understanding of American political development as the interweaving of opposing ideas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFederal governmentzUnited States. 0aFederal government-United States. 0aGoldwater, Barry M.-(Barry Morris),-1909-1998. 0aJohnson, Andrew,-1808-1875. 0aReconstruction (U.S. history, 1865-1877) 0aReconstruction (U.S. history, 1865-1877). 0aUnited States-Politics and government. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican political development.  aAndrew Johnson.  aAnti-Federalists.  aBarry Goldwater.  aFounding.  aNew Deal.  aReconstruction.  aconstitutional moments.  aliberal tradition.  amultiple traditions.1 aMellow, Nicole, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022651529840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226515465423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226515465/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles